Would you really want to leave this *arsenal* of usually very mana efficient fire power out of the game ? I have to agree I used to be a very very light user of AoE spells. I changed my mind for several reasons :<br>
<br>
1/ First of all, how many times have you finished a fight with all the tanks almost half dead, the cleric oom and your pet at full health ? Isn't there space for *some* groups to use different tactics than the rather classic, now boring and sometimes very dangerous, pull/mez/tank and nuke single target one ? Summoning a new pet costs me less than half of what costs a res to a cleric, not to speak of the experience lost if a PC dies. <br>
<br>
2/ Second, we are a class (with necros in a lesser extent) which is &quot;pet-based&quot; and always be. Considering our pet as a &quot;weakness&quot; for a group takes away 75% of our power. When a mob aggros our pet who is supposed to assist the main tank and therefore prevents an enchanter's/bard's mez, most of the time we are incriminated whereas bad pathing, bad position of the tanks or bad timing of the mez might be the true causes. We can all control (backing it off/unsummoning it) our pets at a given level, or at least we should be able to, but using AoE tactics would sometimes lessen this burden on us. <br>
<br>
3/ Everything which makes us stronger and more desired in groups should be supported, or at least considered in some situations. Groups with two mages and a wizard for example are highly uncommon at higher levels, whereas it seems to be one of the most powerful one in theory. Creativity and imagination should never lack to an experienced player.<br>
<br>
I can think of several high level dungeons where this tactic could be perfectly used and with success : LGuk, KC, OS, even in Plane of Fear. In outdoor zones it's even easier. The key would be a good placement/timing of your pets and a good puller. I would use earth pets for the root and the best damage absorbing ability. Buff them like you would like your tanks being buffed. Place them somewhere in front of of the group, quite far way, puller runs targets into the pets and stops behind the pets. Pets start fighting one target each, puller the last one. Let the tank/pets do their job first : don't open on AoE at once. Malise the target your pet is fighting, root and incoming AoE will stick better. Enchanters/Shamans have time to slow all the targets, Wizard to throw an AoE root/snare if needed and then AoE away. They won't come after you, there is no reason they would since your AoE do less damage per target than a usual DD. And we all know how not to overburn right <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ? After several battles, if the pet's health is really too low, either cleric CH it or you summon another one and you are ready again.<br>
<br>
The high regeneration ability of your pets and AoE spells is a deadly combo. Wizards, who have alot of high level AoE spells, magicians who have the best pets, clerics who can focus on only one or two tanks to heal, enchanters who wont die as often because of broken mezzes, I think alot of classes can take advantage of better using it.<br>
<br>
